Sally Kohn has a powerful vision for a more united United States. She's a columnist and a political commentator for CNN, and she is working on a book about hate that will be published in the spring of 2018. As a former contributor to Fox News, this progressive lesbian sparred with some of the most conservative minds on television and has sifted through hundreds of letters of hate mail a day. But she deeply believes in finding our common humanity, political differences aside. Before we can achieve political correctness, we must first establish emotional correctness — and this will ignite conversations that lead to real change.

Kohn has appeared on Fox, MSNBC and CNN and has written for The Daily Beast, Salon, The Atlantic and TIME Magazine.

aws-transcripts.transcript: So people tell me I'm a nice person to the point where it's part of my personal and professional identity that I'm so nice and, uh, able to get along with anyone, even my most fierce opponents. That's like my thing. It's what I'm known for and then, But what no one knows is that I was a bully. Honestly, I didn't think about it much myself. I buried the memories for years. Ah, and even still a lot of it's really hazy. Um, denial, by the way, apparently is also one of my things. But the more people started to praise me for being a liberal who could get along with conservatives, and the more I wrote articles about being nice and gave talks about being nice more, he felt this hypocrisy creeping up inside me. What if I was actually really mean when I was 10 years old? Um, there was a girl in my class at school named Vicky, and I tormented her mercilessly. I mean, everyone did even the teachers picked on her. It doesn't make it any better, does it? Vicky was clearly a troubled kid. She would hit herself and give herself bloody noses and she had hygiene problems should big hygiene problems. But instead of helping this girl who is plainly suffering from hardships in her life, be called her sticky Vicky, I called her sticky Vicky. My clearest memory is standing in the empty hallway outside the fifth grade classrooms, waiting for Vicky to come out of the bathroom, and I have a clipboard in a pen and a survey I've made up asking about shampoo preferences like I'm doing a study for science class or something. And when Vicky comes out of the bathroom, I pounce on her, and I asked her what shampoo she uses. Now, put this in perspective. I can't remember the names of my teachers. I can't remember names off any of the books I read that year. I pretty much can't remember anything from fifth grade, but I remember that Vicky told me she used white rain shampoo, clears yesterday like it just happened, and there's classes let out. I ran down the hall, shouting at all the other kids. Sticky Vicky uses white rain shampoo. Don't use white rain shampoo or you'll smell like sticky Vicky. I forgot about this memory for a long time, When I finally started remembering it, I immediately needed to know more. I reached out to friends and eventually social media, and I did everything I could to try to find Vicki. I needed to know that she was okay. And then I hadn't ruined her life. But what I quickly realized was I wasn't just trying to figure out what happened. Vicky. I was trying to figure out what happened to me when I was 10 years old. I treated another human being like some worthless other. Like I was better than her and she was garbage. What kind of a nice person does that? I mean, I know I was only a kid, but not all kids do that. Most kids don't do that, right? So what if I wasn't nice after all? I was really just a hateful monster. Then I started to notice myself having these mean impulses thinking mean thoughts and wanting to say them. Admittedly, most of my mean thoughts were about conservatives, but not just conservatives. I also call myself thinking mean things about mushy centrists, liberals and greedy Wall Street bankers and islamophobes and slow drivers, because I really hate slow drivers And as I catch myself in these moments of hypocrisy, either they were, I was just noticing the more or they were getting worse, especially in last few years. And as I felt more hateful, rageful, really, I noticed the world around me seemed to be getting more hateful to like There was the steady undercurrent of hate bubbling up all around us and increasingly overflowing. So the plus side, I guess, is that I realized that hate was not just my problem, which is like the most selfish plus side ever, because now, instead of just my own hate and cruelty toe, try to figure out I had a whole world of hate. I wanted to unravel and understand and fix. So I did what all overly intellectual people do when they have a problem they want to understand. And I wrote a book I wrote a book about hate Spoiler alert. I'm against it now. At this point, you might be thinking yourself why you're worried about hate. You didn't hate Vicky. Bullying isn't hate, isn't it? Gordon Alpert, the psychologist who pioneered the study of hate in the early 19 hundreds. He developed what he called a scale of pressure tickets at one end or things like genocide and other bias motivated violence. But the other end are things like believing that your in group is inherently superior to some out group or, you know, avoiding social interaction with those others. Isn't that all hate? I mean, it wasn't an accident that I was a rich kid picking on a poor kid or that Vicky, it turns out, would eventually end up being gay.
